item.title: QLC NAND Arrives For Consumer SSDs
item.description: When NAND flash memory was first used for general purpose storage in the earliest ancestors of modern SSDs, the memory cells were treated as simply binary, storing a single bit of data per cell by switching cells between one of two voltage states. Since then demand for higher capacity has pushed the industry to store more bits in each flash memory cell. In the past year, the deployment of 64-layer 3D NAND flash has allowed almost all of the SSD industry to adopt three bit per cell TLC flash, which only a few short years ago was the cutting edge.

item.title: Windows Store and the 3rd Party App Situation
item.description: So the third party app situation, out of the gate, is the biggest issue I can see with Windows RT. Obviously, with ARM processors, typical x86 legacy programs are out, so you’re forced to rely exclusively on the Windows Store for third-party applications. Within the Windows Store itself, almost all of the applications are compatible with both x86 and ARM architectures - Microsoft claims around 90% off the apps on the Windows Store at launch are compatible with both Windows 8 and Windows RT, and it appears that a lot of developers will be releasing applications on the Store for both platforms simultaneously.

item.title: Vera Putina cause of death
item.description: Vera Nikolaevna Putina, born on September 6, 1926, rose to prominence in 1999 when she claimed that Russian President Vladimir Putin was her son. This allegation contradicted Putin’s official biography, which indicated that his parents died before he took office. While Putina’s assertions may be false or part of a publicity effort, they do highlight holes in the known narrative of Putin’s past. According to the official account, Putin’s parents were already in their forties when he was born, leaving a ten-year gap between the births of their previous sons, Albert and Viktor, who both died as children.
